The paper deals with the complexity of workflow resiliency, which is a security policy analysis for ensuring that a workflow can still be instantiated even when a subset of workers is removed from service. This topic falls under the category of computer security (cs.CR) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI), as it involves policy analysis and constraint-solving technology. The paper also involves complexity theory (cs.LO) and data structures (cs.DS) in its analysis. Lastly, the paper discusses how to reduce workflow resiliency to Answer Set Programming (ASP), which falls under the category of software engineering (cs.SE).
